Now, we need to prove this inequality. To approach this, we can use induction on the structure of the loop walk.

```tactics
  induction p using Loopwalk.rec with
  | nil =>
    simp [Finset.card_singleton]
```

For the base case of `p = nil`, the support set is `{u}` (card 1) and the edge set is `{}` (card 0). So we need to show $1 \leq 0 + 1$, which is true.

```tactics
  | cons h p ih =>
    simp [Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem, Finset.card_singleton] at ih ⊢
    all_goals
      try { tauto }
      try { omega }
```

In the induction step for `cons h p`, the support set is `{u} \cup p.supportSet` and the edge set is `{h} \cup p.edgeSet`. The inequality becomes $1 + |p.supportSet| \leq 1 + |p.edgeSet| + 1$. By the induction hypothesis $|p.supportSet| \leq |p.edgeSet| + 1$, so $1 + |p.supportSet| \leq 1 + (|p.edgeSet| + 1) = |p.edgeSet| + 2 \leq |p.edgeSet| + 1 + 1$ which is true.

```tactics
  | loop p ih =>
    simp [Finset.card_insert_of_not_mem, Finset.card_singleton] at ih ⊢
    all_goals
      try { tauto }
      try { omega }
```

For the loop case, the support set is `{u} \cup p.supportSet` and the edge set is `{(u,u)} \cup p.edgeSet`. The inequality becomes $1 + |p.supportSet| \leq 1 + |p.edgeSet| + 1$. By the induction hypothesis $|p.supportSet| \leq |p.edgeSet| + 1$, so $1 + |p.supportSet| \leq 1 + (|p.edgeSet| + 1) = |p.edgeSet| + 2 \leq |p.edgeSet| + 1 + 1$ which is true.
