The support set of `loop q` is `u :: q.support` (where `u` is the start of the walk). The card of this is `1 + card (q.support)`.
The edge set of `loop q` is `q.edges`. The card of this is `card (q.edges)`.
So we need `1 + card (q.support) ≤ card (q.edges) + 1`, which simplifies to `card (q.support) ≤ card (q.edges)`. This is exactly the induction hypothesis.

```tactics
    all_goals
      try { 
        have h1 : (q.support).card ≤ (q.edges).card := by 
          apply ih
        omega 
      }
```

This should complete the proof. The induction hypothesis `ih` gives `card (q.support) ≤ card (q.edges)`. We need to show `card (q.support) + 1 ≤ card (q.edges) + 1`. This follows directly from `ih`.

The key insight is that both the support set and the edge set are built recursively, and the inequality holds at each step of the recursion, with the induction hypothesis ensuring that the inequality holds for the recursive step.
</think>
